<body>
<p>The Braidy Tester lists his
<a href='http://blogs.msdn.com/micahel/archive/2004/06/16/157202.aspx'>Hallmarks of a Great Developer</a>.
This is a good list to aspire to.  There's not a whole lot of detail here,
but the criteria are hard hard to argue with.
</p>

<p>The one that really resonated with me is "Approaches debugging scientifically".
I've always felt that developing follows the mathematical method
(start with a few primitives, and build up from there),
while debugging followed the scientific method (observe, hypothesize, experiment, and analyze).
</p>

